Trabecula krumpermani
varies widely in the shape of the apex, with variable width of the first whorls. The holotype (
Fig. 62
) is an example of a more pupoid shape, with a less acuminate apex and larger width in the first three whorls; the figured paratype (
Jong & Coomans 1988 : pl. 20 , fig. 678
) and most of the Brazilian material (
Figs. 63−65
), as well as the shell illustrated by
Redfern ( 2001 : pl. 67 . fig. 627 )
, have more acuminate apices.
